@AnneinAK: Your though process is persuasive and I appreciate you thinking through and laying out a possible timeline. However, allow me to briefly lay out an alternative hypothesis and I would love to hear your thoughts:  It seems very unlikely that the Senate will convict and Pelosi knows this. I'm not sure that passing articles of impeachment and then losing the Senate vote is good for Democrats because: 
     a) they then have to drop the matter and can't keep drip-drip-dripping it out there for the next year which is likely to lead to new perhaps unexpected revelations that are much more damaging to Trump; and
     b) they risk appearing to swing voters and their base that they "lost" The democratic base is demanding action.  The current investigation is allowing the Democrats to control more of the new cycle than they have for the last several years, and it's keeping their most vocal and extreme members out of the spotlight and thereby limiting electoral damage in 2020. A reasonable strategic response by Pelosi to the above factors (or "facts" if one agrees with me on them as facts) would be to keep threatening to pass articles soon, but keep finding reasons to delay for another week or two and let the process keeping dripping and controlling news cycles. "Q: When are we going? A: Real soon!"  Democratic leaders' behavior appears to me to be consistent with either the hypothesis you lay out or mine above. They are responding to that pressure by making statements about timing that sound concrete but which are ultimately aspirational and don't commit them to do anything by a specific time.  If so, then I wouldn't hold my breath for articles by EOY.  What do you think?
